																		I dunno if I want to love this or call it a ripoff...
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/turtleboy1017" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(522036); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=522036&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610182976" alt="Turtleboy1017" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=522036)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/turtleboy1017" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(522036); return false;" >Turtleboy1017</a></span> <span class="odate time_1309318699 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">29 Jun 2011 03:38</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1189317">
									

<p>I read this exact story before, in a Japanese manga called Doraemon. It's a manga that has hundreds of short stories about a robot from the future that has dozens of gadgets that do awesome things, such as a device that makes you fly, a door frame that takes you anywhere in the world, etc. etc.</p>
<p>Anyway, I distinctly remembering a gadget he had called &quot;fueru-fueru&quot; which in Japanese means &quot;more and more&quot;. The other character in the manga pours some on his cake that he got, so he can eat more and more. Every minute, the cake would split into two identical copies, no loss of mass, and the only way to stop this was to eat the cake. Anyway, eventually it becomes too much for him, and they end the story simply by rocketing the rest of the cakes away into the depths of space.</p>
<p>Although this is a variation of the story, I can't help but wonder if the author may have gotten the inspiration from it. In fact, dozens of SCP's could be inspired by the gadgets Doraemon had.</p>
<p><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doraemon">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doraemon</a></p>

							</div>

								
					
