			<div class="content" id="post-content-4010168">
									

<p>Nope. The event horizon corresponding to a stable black hole of the same mass would be increasing faster than light, but the actual physical event horizon cannot expand faster than light. Gravitational influences travel at the speed of light.</p>
<p>This assumes that cakes can replicate while being torn apart by relativistic oscillations and being thrown into quantum foam, or whatever weird stuff happens inside black holes. It also assumes that creation of mass <em>ex nihilo</em> doesn't change any other physical laws.</p>
<p>(Also, it's possible the event horizon wouldn't increase at all. The event horizon isn't a measure of what's inside the black hole so much as an effect of things falling inside. Whatever happens inside a black hole can't affect the outside.)</p>

